date_rows.append(r)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...)\"\"\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", unchanged_keys)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n(Simplify the duplicated `existing.update(...)` line above — just build the dict directly from one `fetchall()` per chunk.) This turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900) for reads and 3 bulk writes total.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (filters.py:11-27)\n\n`_compile(include)` and `_compile(exclude)` re-compile the same regex list from scratch **inside `match()`, which runs once per job**:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFor a few thousand jobs and a handful of keywords, that's thousands of redundant `re.compile()` calls. Compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nAnd change `match()` to accept pre-compiled `list[re.Pattern]` directly instead of calling `_compile` internally.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` hashed twice per write (models.py:66-69, store.py:67-97)\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` (SHA-256 over title/location/url/department), not cached. In `Store.diff()`, it's computed once for the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and then computed **again** inside `_insert`/`_update` via `job.to_row()`. Minor per-call cost, but doubled across every changed/new job for no reason. Compute it once and pass it through:\n\n```python\nh = job.content_hash\nr = {**job.to_row(), \"content_hash\": h}  # to_row() already sets this; just avoid recomputation\n```\nor simpler: have `to_row()` take the hash as an optional pre-computed arg, or just call `job.content_hash` once per job in `diff()` and reuse the value everywhere (including the write dict) rather than letting `to_row()` recompute it.\n\n## 4. Memory retention — full `raw` payloads kept for large boards (fetchers.py)\n\nMost bespoke parsers (Google, Meta, Microsoft, Netflix, Amazon, D.E. Shaw, Two Sigma, Optiver) deliberately trim `raw` to a small dict — good. But the generic ATS parsers (`parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `parse_ashby`, `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`) keep the **entire** source JSON object in `raw=j`, and `Job.raw` is never used downstream except being dropped in `to_row()` (models.py:73: `d.pop(\"raw\", None)`). For a company with a large Greenhouse/Lever board, that's the full JSON blob per job held in memory for the whole pipeline run for a field nothing reads. Either drop `raw` for these parsers too, or make it lazy/optional:\n\n```python\nout.append(Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=company, ..., raw=j if source.get(\"keep_raw\") else {}))\n```\n\nSame fix applies to `parse_lever`, `parse_ashby`, `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`.\n\n## 5. Caching opportunity — Meta's page scrape happens on every run (fetchers.py:541-546)\n\n`fetch_meta` does a full GET of `metacareers.com/jobs` (to scrape `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens) every single run just to extract a few tokens, before making the actual GraphQL POST. That's inherent to how the fetcher works (tokens likely rotate), so not much to cache there — but it's worth noting this is 2 network round-trips where every other fetcher needs 1 (or N for pagination). Not urgent, just flagging it's the most expensive fetcher per row returned.\n\n## Not applicable / already fine\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend in this repo — skipped.\n- `fetch_all` (fetchers.py:767-788): correctly shares one `httpx.AsyncClient` across all sources with a semaphore-bounded concurrency of 8 — no connection-per-request waste.\n- Pagination loops (Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix/Google/Two Sigma/Optiver) already dedupe via a `seen` set and break early on an empty \"fresh\" page — no unbounded fetching.\n\n## Priority\nFix **#1 (N+1 diff)** first — it's the only one that scales with board size in a way that will visibly slow the 12h cron job down as more companies/sources get added. #2 is next-highest-value since it's a one-line change with real payoff at thousands of jobs. #3 and #4 are minor; #5 is just an observation.\n",
